{"title_page": "Margaret Fleming, Countess of Atholl", "text_new": "'''Margaret Fleming, Countess of Atholl''' (1536-1586) was a Scottish courtier and landowner rumoured to be involved in the occult.\n\nShe was a daughter of [[Malcolm Fleming, 3rd Lord Fleming]] and [[Janet Stewart, Lady Fleming]], a daughter of [[James IV of Scotland]].\n\nShe was a courtier and supporter of Mary, Queen of Scots. She is known for stories told about her by her contemporary enemies.\n\n[[Richard Bannatyne]], a secretary of [[John Knox]], recorded a story that when [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] was in childbirth in [[Edinburgh Castle]], Margaret Fleming magically transferred her labour pains to [[Margaret Beaton|Margaret Beaton, Lady Reres]].<ref>Julian Goodare, ''The Scottish Witch-Hunt in Context'' (Manchester, 2002), p. 58: [[Robert Pitcairn (antiquary)|Robert Pitcairn]], [https://archive.org/details/memorialsoftra5100bannuoft/page/174/mode/2up ''Memorials of the transcations in Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. 174].</ref> Bannatyne was an enemy and political opponent of her husband, the Earl of Atholl, who he described as an \"idolator and depender on witches.\"<ref>Robert Pitcairn, ''Memorials of the transcations in Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn October 1570 [[Archibald Douglas, Parson of Douglas|Mr Archibald Douglas]] obtained a jewel that had been made for Mary, Queen of Scots as propaganda for the Scottish succession to the English throne. He showed it to the English diplomat [[Thomas Randolph (diplomat)|Thomas Randolph]], who sent the jewel to London. It was shaped like an antler and showed Mary enthroned with two fighting lions, with the inscription \"Fall what may Fall the Lion shall be Lord of All\", with a motif of intertwined roses and thistles. The allusion is to the prophecy of [[Thomas the Rhymer|Berlington]]. Randolph was horrified by the implications of this piece which he said was a token to be sent to Mary. The jewel was conjectured to have been commissioned by the \"witches of Atholl\", meaning apparently Margaret Fleming, Countess of Atholl, and her daughters, or her companions at [[Dunkeld]] including [[Mary Fleming]] and a French lady in waiting, Marie Pyennes, ([[George Seton, 6th Lord Seton|Lady Seton]]).<ref>Julian Goodare, ''The Scottish Witch-Hunt in Context'' (Manchester, 2002), p. 58: ''Calendar State Papers  Scotland'', vol. 3 (London, 1903), pp. 315, 361-2, 368-70.</ref> Richard Bannatyne also described this jewel.<ref>Robert Pitcairn, [https://archive.org/details/memorialsoftra5100bannuoft/page/60/mode/2up ''Memorials of the transcations in Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. 61].</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 1579 her husband, the Earl of Atholl died at [[Old Kincardine Castle, Auchterarder|Kincardine Castle]], near [[Auchterarder]], soon after attending a banquet at [[Stirling Castle]]. Margaret Fleming was also unwell. A rumour started that they had been poisoned at the request of [[Annabell Murray, Countess of Mar]], her sister-in-law, or [[Regent Morton]].<ref>George Hewitt, ''Scotland Under Morton'' (Edinburgh, 1982), pp. 70-1.</ref> Agnes Graham, the wife of [[William Murray of Tullibardine]], and also a sister-in-law of Margaret Fleming, wrote to Annabell Murray assuring her that the Countess of Atholl's complaints against her were \"forged lies\".<ref>John, 7th Duke of Atholl, ''Chronicles of the Atholl and Tullibardine families'' (Edinburgh, 1908), pp. 44-5.</ref>\n\nShe died in 1586.\n\n==Family==\nShe married Robert Graham, [[Duke of Montrose|Master of Montrose]], by whom she had a son, [[John Graham, 3rd Earl of Montrose]].\n\nShe next married to Thomas Erskine, [[Lord Erskine|Master of Erskine]], younger brother of [[John Erskine, 6th Lord Erskine]].\n\nShe married thirdly [[John Stewart, 4th Earl of Atholl]], by whom she had a son [[John Stewart, 5th Earl of Atholl]] and three daughters:\n*Jean Stewart, wife of [[Sir Duncan Campbell, 1st Baronet]], and mother of [[Colin Campbell of Glenorchy]] \n*Grizel Stewart, wife of [[David Lindsay, 11th Earl of Crawford]]\n*Mary Stewart, wife of [[Francis Hay, 9th Earl of Erroll]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleming, Margaret}}\n[[Category:Scottish countesses|Atholl]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Court of Mary, Queen of Scots]]\n[[Category:1536 births]]\n[[Category:1586 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Margaret Fleming, Countess of Atholl''' (1536-1586) was a Scottish courtier and landowner rumoured to be involved in the occult.\n\nShe was a daughter of [[Malcolm Fleming, 3rd Lord Fleming]] and [[Janet Stewart, Lady Fleming]], a daughter of [[James IV of Scotland]].\n\nShe was a courtier and supporter of Mary, Queen of Scots. She is known for stories told about her by her contemporary enemies.\n\n[[Richard Bannatyne]], a secretary of [[John Knox]], recorded a story that when [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] was in childbirth in [[Edinburgh Castle]], Margaret Fleming magically transferred her labour pains to [[Margaret Beaton|Margaret Beaton, Lady Reres]].<ref>Julian Goodare, ''The Scottish Witch-Hunt in Context'' (Manchester, 2002), p. 58: [[Robert Pitcairn (antiquary)|Robert Pitcairn]], [https://archive.org/details/memorialsoftra5100bannuoft/page/174/mode/2up ''Memorials of the transcations in Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. 174].</ref> Bannatyne was an enemy and political opponent of her husband, the Earl of Atholl, who he described as an \"idolator and depender on witches.\"<ref>Robert Pitcairn, ''Memorials of the transcations in Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. 15.</ref>\n\nIn October 1570 [[Archibald Douglas, Parson of Douglas|Mr Archibald Douglas]] obtained a jewel that had been made for Mary, Queen of Scots as propaganda for the Scottish succession to the English throne. He showed it to the English diplomat [[Thomas Randolph (diplomat)|Thomas Randolph]], who sent the jewel to London. It was shaped like an antler and showed Mary enthroned with two fighting lions, with the inscription \"Fall what may Fall the Lion shall be Lord of All\", with a motif of intertwined roses and thistles. The allusion is to the prophecy of [[Thomas the Rhymer|Berlington]]. Randolph was horrified by the implications of this piece which he said was a token to be sent to Mary. The jewel was conjectured to have been commissioned by the \"witches of Atholl\", meaning apparently Margaret Fleming, Countess of Atholl, and her daughters, or her companions at [[Dunkeld]] including [[Mary Fleming]] and a French lady in waiting, Marie Pyennes, ([[George Seton, 6th Lord Seton|Lady Seton]]).<ref>Julian Goodare, ''The Scottish Witch-Hunt in Context'' (Manchester, 2002), p. 58: ''Calendar State Papers  Scotland'', vol. 3 (London, 1903), pp. 315, 361-2, 368-70.</ref> Richard Bannatyne also described this jewel.<ref>Robert Pitcairn, [https://archive.org/details/memorialsoftra5100bannuoft/page/60/mode/2up ''Memorials of the transcations in Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. 61].</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 1579 her husband, the Earl of Atholl died at [[Old Kincardine Castle, Auchterarder|Kincardine Castle]], near [[Auchterarder]], soon after attending a banquet at [[Stirling Castle]]. Margaret Fleming was also unwell. A rumour started that they had been poisoned at the request of [[Annabell Murray, Countess of Mar]], her sister-in-law, or [[Regent Morton]].<ref>George Hewitt, ''Scotland Under Morton'' (Edinburgh, 1982), pp. 70-1.</ref> Agnes Graham, the wife of [[William Murray of Tullibardine]], and also a sister-in-law of Margaret Fleming, wrote to Annabell Murray assuring her that the Countess of Atholl's complaints against her were \"forged lies\".<ref>John, 7th Duke of Atholl, ''Chronicles of the Atholl and Tullibardine families'' (Edinburgh, 1908), pp. 44-5.</ref>\n\nShe died in 1586.\n\n==Family==\nShe married Robert Graham, [[Duke of Montrose|Master of Montrose]], by whom she had a son, [[John Graham, 3rd Earl of Montrose]].\n\nShe next married to Thomas Erskine, [[Lord Erskine|Master of Erskine]], younger brother of [[John Erskine, 6th Lord Erskine]].\n\nShe married thirdly [[John Stewart, 4th Earl of Atholl]], by whom she had a son [[John Stewart, 5th Earl of Atholl]] and three daughters:\n*Jean Stewart, wife of [[Sir Duncan Campbell, 1st Baronet]] \n*Grizel Stewart, wife of [[David Lindsay, 11th Earl of Crawford]]\n*Mary Stewart, wife of [[Francis Hay, 9th Earl of Erroll]]  \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleming, Margaret}}\n[[Category:Scottish countesses|Atholl]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Court of Mary, Queen of Scots]]\n[[Category:1536 births]]\n[[Category:1586 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Fleming,_Countess_of_Atholl"}
{"title_page": "Indian Foreign Service", "text_new": "{{Infobox\n| title = Indian Foreign Service (IFS)\n| headerstyle = background:#BC8F8F; color:#fff;\n| header1 = Service Overview\n| label2 = Formed\n| data2 =October 9, 1946\n| label3 = Headquarters\n| data3 = [[Secretariat Building, New Delhi|South Block]], [[New Delhi]] \n| label4 = Country\n| data4 = {{Flag|India}}\n| label5 = Training Ground\n| data5 = [[Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute, India|Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute]], [[New Delhi]]\n| label6 = Field of Operation\n| data6 = [[File:Diplomatic missions of India.PNG|175px|Diplomatic missions of India (Blue) & HQ and domestic offices (Green)]]\n| label7 = Controlling Authority\n| data7 = [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]\n| label8 = Legal personality\n| data8 = [[Governmental]]: [[Government Services]]\n| label9 = General Nature\n| data9 = [[Diplomacy]] & [[Foreign policy]]<br />[[Economic diplomacy]]<br />[[International trade|Trade Relations]]<br />[[Defence Diplomacy]]<br />[[Cultural diplomacy]]<br />[[Consul (representative)|Consular Services]]<br />[[Public diplomacy]]<br />[[Intergovernmental organization]]\n| label10 = Preceding Service\n| data10 = [[Indian Civil Service (British India)|Indian Civil Service]]\n| label11 = Cadre Size\n| data11 = 2780 members (Group A - 850 [https://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm]; Group B - 1930)[https://www.scribd.com/document/320040429/External-Affairs#from_embed]\n| header12 = Service Chief\n| label13 = Foreign Secretary\n| data13 = [[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]], IFS\n| header15 = Minister of the Service\n| label16 = [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister of External Affairs]]\n| data16 = [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n}}\nThe '''Indian Foreign Service''' (IFS) is the [[Public administration|administrative]] [[Diplomacy|diplomatic]]<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm|title=MEA - About MEA : Indian Foreign Service|author=|date=|website=www.mea.gov.in|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> [[civil service]] under Group A<ref>[http://www.persmin.nic.in/DOPT/EmployeesCorner/Acts_Rules/ccs(cca)/SCHEDULE-1.PDF Complete Civil Service Schedule of the Civil Services Group A of India] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041434/http://www.persmin.nic.in/DOPT/EmployeesCorner/Acts_Rules/ccs(cca)/SCHEDULE-1.PDF |date=2016-03-04 }}.\" '' Civil Service Group A - Government of India''of the Central Civil Services Group B of India].\" ''Central Civil Service Group B - Government of India'' 1 January 2011.</ref> and Group B<ref>[http://dopt.gov.in/sites/default/files/SCHEDULE-2.pdf Complete Civil Service Schedule of the Central Civil Services Group B of India].\" ''Central Civil Service Group B - Government of India'', 1 January 2011.</ref> of the [[Central Civil Services of India|Central Civil Services]] of the [[executive branch]] of the [[Government of India]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://upsc.gov.in/sites/default/files/Engl_CSP_2017.pdf|title=Examination Notice no. 06/2017-CSP|date=February 22, 2017|website=[[Union Public Service Commission]]|url-status=live|access-date=August 19, 2017}}</ref> It is a Central Civil service as [[Foreign relations of India|Foreign policy]] is the subject matter and prerogative of Union Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.constitution.org/cons/india/shed07.htm|title=SCHEDULE|website=www.constitution.org}}</ref> The [[Ambassador]], [[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]], [[Consul (representative)|Consul General]], [[Permanent Representative of India to the United Nations]] and [[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary]] are some of the offices held by the members of this service.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> The administrative head of the service is the Foreign Secretary, and the Political Head of the service is the External Affairs Minister. \n\nThe service is entrusted to conduct [[diplomacy]] and manage [[foreign relations of India]].<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> It is the body of career [[diplomat]]s serving in more than 162 [[List of diplomatic missions of India|Indian Diplomatic Missions]] and [[List of intergovernmental organizations|International Organisations]] around the world. In addition, they serve at the headquarters of the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External affairs]] in Delhi and the [[Prime Minister's Office (India)|Prime Minister's Office]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/sanjeev-kumar-singla-appointed-ps-to-pm-narendra-modi/article1-1242668.aspx|title=Singla appointed PS to PM Narendra Modi|author=|date=20 July 2014|website=hindustantimes.com|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> They also head the Regional Passport Offices throughout the country and hold positions in the President's Secretariat and several ministries on deputation. [[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary of India]] is the administrative head of the Indian Foreign Service.\n\nIFS was created by the Government of India in October 1946 through a Cabinet note<ref name=\"Bagchi\">{{cite web|last=Bagchi|first=Indrani|title=IFS officials building their own traditions|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/IFS-officials-building-their-own-traditions/articleshow/23921012.cms|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> but its roots can be traced back to the British Raj when the Foreign Department was created to conduct business with the \"Foreign European Powers\".<ref name=\"Website of Ministry of External Affairs, India\">{{cite web|title=Indian Foreign Service|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> IFS Day is celebrated on October 9 every year since 2011 to commemorate the day the Indian Cabinet created the IFS.<ref name=\"Bagchi\"/>\n\nOfficers of the IFS are now recruited by the Government of India on the recommendation of the [[Union Public Service Commission]]. Previous to 1948, some were appointed directly by the then Prime Minister and included former native rulers of India who had integrated their provinces into India apart from known persons like Mohammed Yunus. Fresh recruits to the IFS are trained at [[Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute, India|Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute]] after a brief foundation course at the [[Lal Bahadur Shastri National Academy of Administration]], [[Mussoorie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meafsi.gov.in/|title=Foreign Service Institute|author=|date=|website=meafsi.gov.in|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Delhi India Government.jpg|thumb|[[Secretariat Building, New Delhi|South Block]] The HQ of Ministry of External Affairs, Prime Minister's Office and Defence Ministry in New Delhi]]\n\n[[File:President Obama and Prime Minister Modi in an expanded bilateral meeting at Hyderabad House.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Negotiating exercises like this are routine and vital part of Indian diplomats' job profile. Here, [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Barack Obama|Obama]] and [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi|Modi]] are with their diplomats in an expanded bilateral meeting at [[Hyderabad House]], [[New Delhi]].|alt=]]\n\n[https://www.technicalrab.com/2020/04/passport-online-apply-part-2.html?m=1 On ( click here to apply online passport in hindi )] 13 September 1783, the [[board of directors]] of the [[Honourable East India Company|East India Company]] passed a [[Resolution (law)|resolution]] at [[Fort William, India|Fort William]], [[Calcutta]] (now [[Kolkata]]), to create a department, which could help \"relieve the pressure\" on the [[Warren Hastings]] administration in conducting its \"secret and political business.\"<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> Although established by the Company, the '''Indian Foreign Department''' conducted business with foreign [[Europe]]an powers.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> From the very beginning, a distinction was maintained between the ''foreign'' and ''political'' functions of the Foreign Department; relations with all \"Asiatic powers\" (including native [[princely state]]s) were treated as ''political'', while relations with European powers were treated as ''foreign''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meaindia.nic.in/onmouse/ifs.htm|title=Sorry for the inconvenience.|author=|date=|website=meaindia.nic.in|accessdate=2 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619063509/http://meaindia.nic.in/onmouse/ifs.htm|archive-date=19 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1843, the [[Governor-General of India]], [[Edward Law, 1st Earl of Ellenborough]] carried out administrative reforms, organizing the Secretariat of the Government into four departments: Foreign, Home, Finance, and Military. Each was headed by a secretary-level officer. The Foreign Department Secretary was entrusted with the \"conduct of all correspondence belonging to the external and internal diplomatic relations of the government.\"<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nThe [[Government of India Act 1935]] attempted to delineate more clearly functions of the foreign and political wings of the Foreign Department, it was soon realized that it was administratively imperative to completely bifurcate the department. Consequently, the '''External Affairs Department''' was set up separately under the direct charge of the Governor-General.\n\nThe idea of establishing a separate diplomatic service to handle the external activities of the Government of India originated from a note dated 30 September 1944, recorded by [[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] T. J. Hutton, the Secretary of the Planning and Development Department.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> When this note was referred to the Department of External Affairs for comments, [[Olaf Caroe]], the Foreign Secretary, recorded his comments in an exhaustive note detailing the scope, composition and functions of the proposed service. Caroe pointed out that as India emerged as autonomous, it was imperative to build up a system of representation abroad that would be in complete harmony with the objectives of the future government.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nOn 9 October 1946, the Indian government established the Indian Foreign Service for India's [[Diplomacy|diplomatic]], [[Consul (representative)|consular]] and commercial representation overseas. With independence, there was a near-complete transition of the Foreign and Political Department into what then became the new [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs and Commonwealth Relations]].\n\n== Selection ==\n[[File:Passports Front.jpg|thumb|An Indian Diplomatic Passport and an Official Passport. As opposed to the deep blue passport issued to ordinary Indian citizens, the diplomatic passport is [[maroon]]-coloured with golden 'Diplomatic Passport' engraved on it in English and [[Hindi]].|alt=]]\n\nIn 1948, the first group of Indian Foreign Service officers recruited under the combined [[Civil Services Examination]] administered by the [[Union Public Service Commission]] joined the service.<ref name=\"upsc.gov.in\">http://upsc.gov.in/exams/notifications/2014/csp/CSP%202014%20English.pdf</ref> This exam is still used to select new foreign service officers.\n\nIn recent years, the intake into the Indian Foreign Service has averaged between 16-20 persons annually. The present cadre strength of the service stands at approximately 800 officers manning around 183 Indian missions and posts abroad and the various posts in the Ministry at home (Defence, Finance, Home etc.)\n\n==Training==\nOn acceptance to the Foreign Service, new entrants undergo significant training, which is considered to be one of the most challenging and longest service trainings in the Government of India and nearly takes more than 1 year to graduate from. The entrants undergo a probationary period (and are referred to as Officer Trainees). Training begins at the [[Lal Bahadur Shastri National Academy of Administration]] (LBSNAA) in [[Mussoorie]], where members of many elite Indian civil services are trained.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nAfter completing a 15-week training at the LBSNAA, the probationers join the [[Foreign Service Institute India|Foreign Service Institute]] in [[New Delhi]] for a more intensive training in a host of subjects important to diplomacy, including international relations theory, military diplomacy, trade, India's foreign policy, [[history]], [[International Law|international law]], diplomatic practice, hospitality, protocol and administration. They also go on attachments with different government bodies and defence ([[Indian Army|Army]], [[Indian Navy|Navy]], [[Indian Air Force|Air Force]], [[Central Armed Police Forces|CAPF]]) establishments and undertake tours both in India and abroad. The entire training programme lasts for a period of 12 months.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nUpon the completion of the training programme at the Institute, the officer is assigned a compulsory foreign language (CFL). After a brief period of desk attachment in the Ministry of External Affairs, at the rank of Assistant Secretary, the officer is posted to an [[Diplomatic missions of India|Indian diplomatic mission]] abroad where her/his CFL is the native language. There the officer undergoes language training and is expected to develop proficiency in the CFL and pass an examination before being allowed to continue in the service.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\n==Functions==\n[[File:Secretary Clinton Meets With Indian Ambassador Rao (6762166815).jpg|thumb|Then [[Indian Ambassador to the United States]], [[Nirupama Rao]], in a meeting with then [[U.S. Secretary of State]], [[Hillary Clinton]], in [[Washington, D.C.]], 2012]]\n[[File:High Commission of India, Canberra.jpg|thumb|Indian High Commission in [[Canberra]]]]\n\nAs a career diplomat, the Foreign Service Officer is required to project India\u2019s interests, both at home and abroad on a wide variety of issues. These include bilateral political and economic cooperation, trade and investment promotion, cultural interaction, press and media liaison as well as a whole host of multilateral issues.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nSubmission of a copy of the [[credential]] is the official beginning of any Ambassador's tenure in the host country. It is an attestation of qualification, competence, or authority issued to an Ambassador by the Head of the State with a relevant or de facto authority or assumed competence to do so.\n\n'''The functions of an Indian diplomat may be summarized as:'''<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nRepresenting India in his/her Embassies, High Commissions, Consulates, and Permanent Missions to multilateral organizations like UN;\n\nProtecting India\u2019s national interests in the country of his/her posting;\n\nPromoting friendly relations with the receiving state as also its people, including [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|NRI/PIOs]];\n\nReporting accurately on developments in the country of posting which are likely to influence the formulation of India\u2019s policies;\n\nNegotiating agreements on various issues with the authorities of the receiving state; and\n\nExtending consular facilities to foreigners and Indian nationals abroad.\n\n'''At home'''<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nMinistry of External Affairs is responsible for all aspects of external relations. Territorial divisions deal with bilateral political and economic work while functional divisions look after policy planning, multilateral organizations, regional groupings, legal matters, disarmament, protocol, consular, Indian Diaspora, press and publicity, administration and other aspects.\n\n==Career and rank structure==\n[[File:Diplomatic hierarchy.png|thumb|165px|The hierarchy in foreign service]]\n[[File:Foreign_Secretary_Shringla_29_January_2020.jpg|thumb|230px|right|[[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]] is the 33rd [[Foreign Secretary of India]] and administrative head of the Indian Foreign Service & Foreign Service Board]]\n*'''At an [[Diplomatic mission|embassy]]''': ''in ascending order of rank''\n**Third Secretary (entry level)\n**Second Secretary (promotion upon being confirmed in service)\n**First Secretary\n**[[Minister-counselor|Counsellor]]\n**[[Minister (government)|Minister]]\n**Deputy Chief of Mission/Deputy High Commissioner/Deputy Permanent Representative\n**[[Ambassador]]/[[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]]/[[Permanent Representative]]\n*'''At the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]''': ''in ascending order of rank''\n**Assistant Secretary/Under Secretary\n**Deputy Secretary\n**Director\n**[[Joint Secretary to Government of India|Joint Secretary]]\n**Additional Secretary\n**[[Secretary to Government of India|Secretary]]\n**'''[[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary of India]]''' (India's Top Diplomat, Administrative Head of the Indian Foreign Service & Foreign Service Board)\n\n==Major concerns and Reforms==\n{{see also|Devyani Khobragade incident}}\n\nIn 2010, a diplomat officer was found spying for an intelligence agency of another country and was later jailed for three years.<ref name=\"IFS Resent RAW\">{{cite web|title=Madhuri deeply resentful of IFS, her arrest blew RAW officer's cover|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/madhuri-deeply-resentful-of-ifs-her-arrest-blew-raw-officers-cover/612850/|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Spy Pakistan\">{{cite web|title=Story of Madhuri Gupta: A Diplomat Who Turned \u2018Spy\u2019 For Pakistan|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/india/madhuri-gupta-spy-for-pakistan-espionage-case|publisher=[[The Quint]]|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"LAdy grouses\">{{cite web|title=The Lady With The Grouses|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/the-lady-with-the-grouses/265275|publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Spy Jail\">{{cite web|title=Falling in love with Pakistani spy cost Madhuri Gupta reputation, career & 3 years in jail|url=https://theprint.in/defence/falling-in-love-with-pakistani-spy-cost-madhuri-gupta-reputation-career-3-years-in-jail/60916/|publisher=The Print[|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> In 2012, media reports showed that a foreign service officer was fined US$1.5 million<ref name=\"IFS Fine Slavery\">{{cite web|title=US judge: Pay $1.5 m to maid of Indian diplomat for ill treatment|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/us-judge-pay-1-5-m-to-maid-of-indian-diplomat-for-ill-treatment/|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS torture\">{{cite web|title=US court asks Indian diplomat to pay $1.5m to 'tortured' maid|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/us-canada-news/US-court-asks-Indian-diplomat-to-pay-1-5m-to-tortured-maid/articleshow/12010886.cms|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> for engaging in slavery <ref name=\"IFS Fine Slavery\"/> by [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]]<ref name=\"IFS Fine Slavery\"/> and was also found denying visa on the basis of homosexuality.<ref name=\"IFS Visa denial 2012\">{{cite web|title=IFS officer denies visa to spouse of gay American diplomat, moved out|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/ifs-officer-denies-visa-to-spouse-of-gay-diplomat-is-moved-out/1201023/|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Visa 2012\">{{cite web|title=IFS officer refuses visa to gay diplomat's spouse, transferred|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/ifs-officer-refuses-visa-to-gay-diplomats-spouse-transferred-1257167.html|publisher=[[Firstpost]]|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Shashi Tharoor]], currently the Chairman of the Parliamentary Standing Committee on External Affairs,<ref name=\"Lok Sabha\">{{cite web |url=http://164.100.47.192/Loksabha/Committee/Chairmen_Committees.aspx |title=Chairperson of Committees - Lok Sabha |work=[[Lok Sabha]] |accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rajya Sabha\">{{cite web |url=http://164.100.47.5/webcom/typewise.aspx?type=DRSCLS |title=Department Related Parliamentary Standing Committees (LS) |work=[[Rajya Sabha]] |accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> has presented 12th report<ref name=\"EA 12th Report IFS\">{{cite web |url=http://164.100.47.193/lsscommittee/External%20Affairs/16_External_Affairs_12.pdf |title=Twelfth Report, Standing Committee on External Affairs: IFS cadre|work=[[Lok Sabha]] |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> for expanding and building the numbers, quality and capacity of India's diplomats.<ref name=\"Shashi Tharoor Panel IFS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/india-is-strapped-for-diplomats-but-if-shashi-tharoors-panel-has-its-way-you-could-become-one-2931362.html |title=If Shashi Tharoor's panel has its way, India's diplomatic corps could grow in quantity and quality |work=[[Firstpost]] |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Gap\">{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/fill-in-ifs-cadre-gap-parliament-committee-to-government/articleshow/53532710.cms |title=Fill in IFS cadre gap, Parliament committee to Government|work=[[The Economic Times]] |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> It has been reported that India's diplomatic corps is increasingly outclassed, outnumbered and out of date.<ref name=\"IFS MEA O\">{{cite web |url=https://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/ministry-eternal-affairs-0 |title=In the Ministry of Eternal Affairs|work=[[The Caravan]] |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> India has one of the most understaffed diplomatic force of any major country in the world.<ref name=\"IFS India US China\">{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/opinion/india-must-rethink-strategies-on-national-security-if-it-wants-to-join-ranks-with-us-china/270324/ |title=India must rethink strategies on national security if it wants to join ranks with US, China|work=The Print |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Foreign Influence\">{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/diplomacy/with-just-1400-diplomats-indias-foreign-influence-is-severely-limited/219288/ |title=With just 1,400 diplomats, India\u2019s foreign influence is severely limited|work=The Print |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Global\">{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/india/governance/india-has-global-ambitions-but-not-enough-ifs-officers-to-fulfil-them/108990/ |title=India has global ambitions but not enough IFS officers to fulfil them|work=The Print |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS relevance\">{{cite web |url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/indian-foreign-service-in-desperate-need-of-reform-particularly-when-it-is-losing-relevance-2943924.html |title=Indian Foreign Service in desperate need of reform, particularly when it is losing relevance|work=[[Firstpost]] |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Corruption and others===\nSeveral media reports have reported foreign service officers under investigation for corruption,<ref name=\"IFS Exchequer\">{{cite web|title=Milking the exchequer not foreign to IFS babus|url=https://timesofindia.com/india/Milking-the-exchequer-not-foreign-to-IFS-babus/articleshow/47873988.cms|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS CBI\">{{cite web|title=CBI to summon IFS officer Rakesh Kumar for questioning|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/cbi-to-summon-ifs-officer-rakesh-kumar-for-questioning/377172|publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Scandal\">{{cite web|title=Scandal in Indian Foreign Service, 2 officers booked|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/mea-292292.html|publisher=[[CNN-News18]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS UK\">{{cite web|title=Indian diplomats in UK face corruption allegations|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/20070430-corruption-allegations-to-uk-posted-indian-diplomats-748793-2007-04-30|publisher=[[India Today]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> sexual assault<ref name=\"IFS Sex Assault\">{{cite web|title=Woman Accuses IFS Officer of Sexual Assault|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/woman-accuses-ifs-officer-of-sexual-assault/703628/?next|publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> and financial irregularities for {{INRConvert|15|l|year=2020|lk=on}} per month.<ref name=\"IFS Financial\">{{cite web|title=Senior diplomat, who rented house for Rs 15 lakh a month, recalled for financial irregularities|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2019/dec/29/senior-diplomat-who-rented-house-for-rs-15-lakh-a-month-recalled-for-financial-irregularities-2082472.html|publisher=[[The New Indian Express]]|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign Service cadre discrimination===\nThere is in total a pool of 2,780 personnel holding diplomatic rank that serve in overseas missions and at headquarters. Of these only a minority of about 850 [https://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm] are IFS officers, the senior cadre of Indian diplomacy, which is primarily drawn from recruitment through the Civil Services Examination. The breakdown of other cadres and personnel include 252 Grade-I officers of the IFS(B), 33 of the Interpreters Cadre, 24 of the Legal and Treaties Cadre, 635 Attaches, 540 diplomatic officers from the secretarial staff and 310 diplomatic officers from other Ministries.[https://www.scribd.com/document/320040429/External-Affairs#from_embed External Affairs | Test (Assessment) | Public Administration]\n\nIFS (B) is the subordinate cadre which ranks below the IFS (A) and has two sub-cadres, the IFS (B) General Cadre (recruited as Clerks and Assistants (now Assistant Section Officers)) and Stenographers Cadre (recruited as Stenographers and Personal Assistants) through separate entrance exams conducted by the Staff Selection Commission. The General Cadre, after promotion to Grade-I of the IFS (B), are absorbed into the IFS A service, while the Stenographers Cadre was denied this benefit vide a ruling in 2004 banning the lateral entry into IFS (A) upon promotion as Principal Private Secretaries (equivalent to Under Secretary in the IFS (B) General Cadre).<ref name=\"complaint\">{{cite news|last1=Mitra|first1=Devirupa|title=The class war in Foreign Service|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/The-class-war-in-Foreign-Service/2013/11/03/article1870174.ece1|publisher=New Indian Express|date=November 3, 2013}}</ref> The Stenographers Cadre provides secretarial support to the IFS Officers, while the IFS (B) General Cadre provides clerical support by manning the Sections and handling the files.<ref name=\"stenographer\">{{cite news|title=From steno to ambassador|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/article528329.ece?service=print|publisher=New Indian Express|date=May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe relations between the cadres have been marked by territorial grievance and rivalry, becoming at times heated enough to spill into the public sphere.<ref name=\"complaint\"/> A common grievance among IFS (A) officers is the practice of antedating the appointment of IFS (B) officers 8 years before the date of their actual promotion.<ref name=\"complaint\"/> This puts the IFS (B) officers, who are seen as less prestigious, ahead for promotions of IFS (A) officers who directly entered the service before them.<ref name=\"complaint\"/> In 2013, 6 IFS (A) officers went as far as to lodge a complaint, against their foreign secretary as well as eight IFS (B) officers named as respondents, with the Central Administrative Tribunal (CAT) for clogging the promotion pipeline and leading to \"de-motivation and demoralisation among direct recruit officers\".<ref name=\"complaint\"/>\n\nIFS (B) officers have also complained of discrimination against them by IFS (A) officers. A Facebook group purportedly voicing the objections of IFS (B) officers sprung up in 2016 when IFS (B) officer Tajinder Singh, Second Secretary in the Indian embassy in [[Lisbon]] died of an apparent suicide.<ref name=\"unrest\">{{cite news|title=MEA facing unrest among junior IFS-B officers|url=http://www.indianmandarins.com/mea-facing-unrest-among-junior-ifs-b-officers/|publisher=Indian Mandarins|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref> The Facebook group alleged that Singh was treated unfairly because he was forced to yield his choice assignment in Washington DC after serving in a hardship posting in [[Damascus]].<ref name=\"unrest\"/> He was forced to give up his choice assignment for Lisbon because of alleged \"discrimination and professional challenges from IFS (A) officers in the ministry\".<ref name=\"unrest\"/>\n\nIFS (B) General Cadre have an acrimonious rivalry with the IFS (B) Stenographers Cadre, who are perceived to be lower in prestige than the IFS (B) officers but have a closer working relationship with IFS (A) officers, giving the stenographers at times promotion opportunities ahead of IFS (B) officers. This rivalry was brought to the fore when an officer of the stenographer cadre was appointed as Indian Ambassador to North Korea in 2012. Within a week of the appointment IFS (B) officers vociferously protested. Three different associations representing IFS (B) officers came together to write a single complaint to the Prime Minister\u2019s Office and the external affairs minister expressing their \u201cutter disappointment\u201d and requesting a review of the appointment. In this fight, the overall loss is for the Government of India since it fails to utilise services of the vast resource of experienced officers of the Stenographers Cadre, who by virtue of their attachments with senior officers, are better equipped of the soft policies of the Government in addition to the rules & regulations, compared to the General Cadre, who are mainly deployed in Sections and are limited to clerical work and maintaining files, till their promotion as Grade I. It has been a demand of the Stenographers Cadre that the Government should introduce merit-based scheme or a common exam for the subordinate cadres (Clerks as well as Stenographers) to select the best and the brightest officers for inclusion into the IFS (A) and filter out the incapable ones.<ref name=\"stenographer\"/>\n\n==Notable IFS Officers==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Vijayalakshmi Pandit]]\n*[[K.P.S. Menon]]\n*[[Maharaja Krishna Rasgotra]]\n*[[Shivshankar Menon]]\n*[[Nirupama Rao]]\n*[[Subimal Dutt]]\n*[[Kanwal Sibal]]\n*[[C. B. Muthamma]]\n*[[Shyam Saran]]\n*[[K. M. Panikkar]]\n*[[Triloki Nath Kaul]]\n*[[Brajesh Mishra]]\n*[[K. R. Narayanan]]\n*[[J N Dixit]]\n*[[Natwar Singh|K. Natwar Singh]]\n*[[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]\n*[[Mohammad Hamid Ansari]]\n*[[Hardeep Singh Puri]]\n*[[Sujatha Singh]]\n*[[S Jaishankar]]\n*[[Vijay Keshav Gokhale]]\n*[[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]]\n*[[Syed Akbaruddin]]\n*[[Vikas Swarup]]\n*[[Arundhati Ghose]]\n*[[Meira Kumar]]\n*[[Salman Haider]]\n*[[Shashank (diplomat) | Shashank]]\n{{div col end}}k\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website |1=http://mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm |name=Official website within the Ministry of External Affairs}}\n*[http://fsi.mea.gov.in/ Official website of Foreign Service Institute India]\n\n{{Public Services of India}}\n{{Civil service}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Service}}\n[[Category:Central Civil Services (India)]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of India]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic services|Indian Foreign Service]]\n[[Category:Indian Foreign Service officers| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox\n| title = Indian Foreign Service (IFS)\n| headerstyle = background:#BC8F8F; color:#fff;\n| header1 = Service Overview\n| label2 = Formed\n| data2 =October 9, 1946\n| label3 = Headquarters\n| data3 = [[Secretariat Building, New Delhi|South Block]], [[New Delhi]] \n| label4 = Country\n| data4 = {{Flag|India}}\n| label5 = Training Ground\n| data5 = [[Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute, India|Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute]], [[New Delhi]]\n| label6 = Field of Operation\n| data6 = [[File:Diplomatic missions of India.PNG|175px|Diplomatic missions of India (Blue) & HQ and domestic offices (Green)]]\n| label7 = Controlling Authority\n| data7 = [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]\n| label8 = Legal personality\n| data8 = [[Governmental]]: [[Government Services]]\n| label9 = General Nature\n| data9 = [[Diplomacy]] & [[Foreign policy]]<br />[[Economic diplomacy]]<br />[[International trade|Trade Relations]]<br />[[Defence Diplomacy]]<br />[[Cultural diplomacy]]<br />[[Consul (representative)|Consular Services]]<br />[[Public diplomacy]]<br />[[Intergovernmental organization]]\n| label10 = Preceding Service\n| data10 = [[Indian Civil Service (British India)|Indian Civil Service]]\n| label11 = Cadre Size\n| data11 = 2780 members (Group A - 850 [https://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm]; Group B - 1930)[https://www.scribd.com/document/320040429/External-Affairs#from_embed]\n| header12 = Service Chief\n| label13 = Foreign Secretary\n| data13 = [[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]], IFS\n| header15 = Minister of the Service\n| label16 = [[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Minister of External Affairs]]\n| data16 = [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n}}\nThe '''Indian Foreign Service''' (IFS) is the [[Public administration|administrative]] [[Diplomacy|diplomatic]]<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm|title=MEA - About MEA : Indian Foreign Service|author=|date=|website=www.mea.gov.in|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> [[civil service]] under Group A<ref>[http://www.persmin.nic.in/DOPT/EmployeesCorner/Acts_Rules/ccs(cca)/SCHEDULE-1.PDF Complete Civil Service Schedule of the Civil Services Group A of India] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041434/http://www.persmin.nic.in/DOPT/EmployeesCorner/Acts_Rules/ccs(cca)/SCHEDULE-1.PDF |date=2016-03-04 }}.\" '' Civil Service Group A - Government of India''of the Central Civil Services Group B of India].\" ''Central Civil Service Group B - Government of India'' 1 January 2011.</ref> and Group B<ref>[http://dopt.gov.in/sites/default/files/SCHEDULE-2.pdf Complete Civil Service Schedule of the Central Civil Services Group B of India].\" ''Central Civil Service Group B - Government of India'', 1 January 2011.</ref> of the [[Central Civil Services of India|Central Civil Services]] of the [[executive branch]] of the [[Government of India]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://upsc.gov.in/sites/default/files/Engl_CSP_2017.pdf|title=Examination Notice no. 06/2017-CSP|date=February 22, 2017|website=[[Union Public Service Commission]]|url-status=live|access-date=August 19, 2017}}</ref> It is a Central Civil service as [[Foreign relations of India|Foreign policy]] is the subject matter and prerogative of Union Government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.constitution.org/cons/india/shed07.htm|title=SCHEDULE|website=www.constitution.org}}</ref> The [[Ambassador]], [[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]], [[Consul (representative)|Consul General]], [[Permanent Representative of India to the United Nations]] and [[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary]] are some of the offices held by the members of this service.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> The administrative head of the service is the Foreign Secretary, and the Political Head of the service is the External Affairs Minister. \n\nThe service is entrusted to conduct [[diplomacy]] and manage [[foreign relations of India]].<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> It is the body of career [[diplomat]]s serving in more than 162 [[List of diplomatic missions of India|Indian Diplomatic Missions]] and [[List of intergovernmental organizations|International Organisations]] around the world. In addition, they serve at the headquarters of the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External affairs]] in Delhi and the [[Prime Minister's Office (India)|Prime Minister's Office]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/sanjeev-kumar-singla-appointed-ps-to-pm-narendra-modi/article1-1242668.aspx|title=Singla appointed PS to PM Narendra Modi|author=|date=20 July 2014|website=hindustantimes.com|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref> They also head the Regional Passport Offices throughout the country and hold positions in the President's Secretariat and several ministries on deputation. [[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary of India]] is the administrative head of the Indian Foreign Service.\n\nIFS was created by the Government of India in October 1946 through a Cabinet note<ref name=\"Bagchi\">{{cite web|last=Bagchi|first=Indrani|title=IFS officials building their own traditions|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/IFS-officials-building-their-own-traditions/articleshow/23921012.cms|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> but its roots can be traced back to the British Raj when the Foreign Department was created to conduct business with the \"Foreign European Powers\".<ref name=\"Website of Ministry of External Affairs, India\">{{cite web|title=Indian Foreign Service|url=http://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> IFS Day is celebrated on October 9 every year since 2011 to commemorate the day the Indian Cabinet created the IFS.<ref name=\"Bagchi\"/>\n\nOfficers of the IFS are now recruited by the Government of India on the recommendation of the [[Union Public Service Commission]]. Previous to 1948, some were appointed directly by the then Prime Minister and included former native rulers of India who had integrated their provinces into India apart from known persons like Mohammed Yunus. Fresh recruits to the IFS are trained at [[Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute, India|Sushma Swaraj Foreign Service Institute]] after a brief foundation course at the [[Lal Bahadur Shastri National Academy of Administration]], [[Mussoorie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meafsi.gov.in/|title=Foreign Service Institute|author=|date=|website=meafsi.gov.in|accessdate=2 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Delhi India Government.jpg|thumb|[[Secretariat Building, New Delhi|South Block]] The HQ of Ministry of External Affairs, Prime Minister's Office and Defence Ministry in New Delhi]]\n\n[[File:President Obama and Prime Minister Modi in an expanded bilateral meeting at Hyderabad House.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Negotiating exercises like this are routine and vital part of Indian diplomats' job profile. Here, [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Barack Obama|Obama]] and [[Prime Minister of India|Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi|Modi]] are with their diplomats in an expanded bilateral meeting at [[Hyderabad House]], [[New Delhi]].|alt=]]\n\nOn 13 September 1783, the [[board of directors]] of the [[Honourable East India Company|East India Company]] passed a [[Resolution (law)|resolution]] at [[Fort William, India|Fort William]], [[Calcutta]] (now [[Kolkata]]), to create a department, which could help \"relieve the pressure\" on the [[Warren Hastings]] administration in conducting its \"secret and political business.\"<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> Although established by the Company, the '''Indian Foreign Department''' conducted business with foreign [[Europe]]an powers.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> From the very beginning, a distinction was maintained between the ''foreign'' and ''political'' functions of the Foreign Department; relations with all \"Asiatic powers\" (including native [[princely state]]s) were treated as ''political'', while relations with European powers were treated as ''foreign''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meaindia.nic.in/onmouse/ifs.htm|title=Sorry for the inconvenience.|author=|date=|website=meaindia.nic.in|accessdate=2 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619063509/http://meaindia.nic.in/onmouse/ifs.htm|archive-date=19 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1843, the [[Governor-General of India]], [[Edward Law, 1st Earl of Ellenborough]] carried out administrative reforms, organizing the Secretariat of the Government into four departments: Foreign, Home, Finance, and Military. Each was headed by a secretary-level officer. The Foreign Department Secretary was entrusted with the \"conduct of all correspondence belonging to the external and internal diplomatic relations of the government.\"<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nThe [[Government of India Act 1935]] attempted to delineate more clearly functions of the foreign and political wings of the Foreign Department, it was soon realized that it was administratively imperative to completely bifurcate the department. Consequently, the '''External Affairs Department''' was set up separately under the direct charge of the Governor-General.\n\nThe idea of establishing a separate diplomatic service to handle the external activities of the Government of India originated from a note dated 30 September 1944, recorded by [[Lieutenant-General (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-General]] T. J. Hutton, the Secretary of the Planning and Development Department.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/> When this note was referred to the Department of External Affairs for comments, [[Olaf Caroe]], the Foreign Secretary, recorded his comments in an exhaustive note detailing the scope, composition and functions of the proposed service. Caroe pointed out that as India emerged as autonomous, it was imperative to build up a system of representation abroad that would be in complete harmony with the objectives of the future government.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nOn 9 October 1946, the Indian government established the Indian Foreign Service for India's [[Diplomacy|diplomatic]], [[Consul (representative)|consular]] and commercial representation overseas. With independence, there was a near-complete transition of the Foreign and Political Department into what then became the new [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs and Commonwealth Relations]].\n\n== Selection ==\n[[File:Passports Front.jpg|thumb|An Indian Diplomatic Passport and an Official Passport. As opposed to the deep blue passport issued to ordinary Indian citizens, the diplomatic passport is [[maroon]]-coloured with golden 'Diplomatic Passport' engraved on it in English and [[Hindi]].|alt=]]\n\nIn 1948, the first group of Indian Foreign Service officers recruited under the combined [[Civil Services Examination]] administered by the [[Union Public Service Commission]] joined the service.<ref name=\"upsc.gov.in\">http://upsc.gov.in/exams/notifications/2014/csp/CSP%202014%20English.pdf</ref> This exam is still used to select new foreign service officers.\n\nIn recent years, the intake into the Indian Foreign Service has averaged between 16-20 persons annually. The present cadre strength of the service stands at approximately 800 officers manning around 183 Indian missions and posts abroad and the various posts in the Ministry at home (Defence, Finance, Home etc.)\n\n==Training==\nOn acceptance to the Foreign Service, new entrants undergo significant training, which is considered to be one of the most challenging and longest service trainings in the Government of India and nearly takes more than 1 year to graduate from. The entrants undergo a probationary period (and are referred to as Officer Trainees). Training begins at the [[Lal Bahadur Shastri National Academy of Administration]] (LBSNAA) in [[Mussoorie]], where members of many elite Indian civil services are trained.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nAfter completing a 15-week training at the LBSNAA, the probationers join the [[Foreign Service Institute India|Foreign Service Institute]] in [[New Delhi]] for a more intensive training in a host of subjects important to diplomacy, including international relations theory, military diplomacy, trade, India's foreign policy, [[history]], [[International Law|international law]], diplomatic practice, hospitality, protocol and administration. They also go on attachments with different government bodies and defence ([[Indian Army|Army]], [[Indian Navy|Navy]], [[Indian Air Force|Air Force]], [[Central Armed Police Forces|CAPF]]) establishments and undertake tours both in India and abroad. The entire training programme lasts for a period of 12 months.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nUpon the completion of the training programme at the Institute, the officer is assigned a compulsory foreign language (CFL). After a brief period of desk attachment in the Ministry of External Affairs, at the rank of Assistant Secretary, the officer is posted to an [[Diplomatic missions of India|Indian diplomatic mission]] abroad where her/his CFL is the native language. There the officer undergoes language training and is expected to develop proficiency in the CFL and pass an examination before being allowed to continue in the service.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\n==Functions==\n[[File:Secretary Clinton Meets With Indian Ambassador Rao (6762166815).jpg|thumb|Then [[Indian Ambassador to the United States]], [[Nirupama Rao]], in a meeting with then [[U.S. Secretary of State]], [[Hillary Clinton]], in [[Washington, D.C.]], 2012]]\n[[File:High Commission of India, Canberra.jpg|thumb|Indian High Commission in [[Canberra]]]]\n\nAs a career diplomat, the Foreign Service Officer is required to project India\u2019s interests, both at home and abroad on a wide variety of issues. These include bilateral political and economic cooperation, trade and investment promotion, cultural interaction, press and media liaison as well as a whole host of multilateral issues.<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nSubmission of a copy of the [[credential]] is the official beginning of any Ambassador's tenure in the host country. It is an attestation of qualification, competence, or authority issued to an Ambassador by the Head of the State with a relevant or de facto authority or assumed competence to do so.\n\n'''The functions of an Indian diplomat may be summarized as:'''<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nRepresenting India in his/her Embassies, High Commissions, Consulates, and Permanent Missions to multilateral organizations like UN;\n\nProtecting India\u2019s national interests in the country of his/her posting;\n\nPromoting friendly relations with the receiving state as also its people, including [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|NRI/PIOs]];\n\nReporting accurately on developments in the country of posting which are likely to influence the formulation of India\u2019s policies;\n\nNegotiating agreements on various issues with the authorities of the receiving state; and\n\nExtending consular facilities to foreigners and Indian nationals abroad.\n\n'''At home'''<ref name=\"mea.gov.in\"/>\n\nMinistry of External Affairs is responsible for all aspects of external relations. Territorial divisions deal with bilateral political and economic work while functional divisions look after policy planning, multilateral organizations, regional groupings, legal matters, disarmament, protocol, consular, Indian Diaspora, press and publicity, administration and other aspects.\n\n==Career and rank structure==\n[[File:Diplomatic hierarchy.png|thumb|165px|The hierarchy in foreign service]]\n[[File:Foreign_Secretary_Shringla_29_January_2020.jpg|thumb|230px|right|[[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]] is the 33rd [[Foreign Secretary of India]] and administrative head of the Indian Foreign Service & Foreign Service Board]]\n*'''At an [[Diplomatic mission|embassy]]''': ''in ascending order of rank''\n**Third Secretary (entry level)\n**Second Secretary (promotion upon being confirmed in service)\n**First Secretary\n**[[Minister-counselor|Counsellor]]\n**[[Minister (government)|Minister]]\n**Deputy Chief of Mission/Deputy High Commissioner/Deputy Permanent Representative\n**[[Ambassador]]/[[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissioner]]/[[Permanent Representative]]\n*'''At the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]''': ''in ascending order of rank''\n**Assistant Secretary/Under Secretary\n**Deputy Secretary\n**Director\n**[[Joint Secretary to Government of India|Joint Secretary]]\n**Additional Secretary\n**[[Secretary to Government of India|Secretary]]\n**'''[[Foreign Secretary (India)|Foreign Secretary of India]]''' (India's Top Diplomat, Administrative Head of the Indian Foreign Service & Foreign Service Board)\n\n==Major concerns and Reforms==\n{{see also|Devyani Khobragade incident}}\n\nIn 2010, a diplomat officer was found spying for an intelligence agency of another country and was later jailed for three years.<ref name=\"IFS Resent RAW\">{{cite web|title=Madhuri deeply resentful of IFS, her arrest blew RAW officer's cover|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/madhuri-deeply-resentful-of-ifs-her-arrest-blew-raw-officers-cover/612850/|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Spy Pakistan\">{{cite web|title=Story of Madhuri Gupta: A Diplomat Who Turned \u2018Spy\u2019 For Pakistan|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/india/madhuri-gupta-spy-for-pakistan-espionage-case|publisher=[[The Quint]]|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"LAdy grouses\">{{cite web|title=The Lady With The Grouses|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/the-lady-with-the-grouses/265275|publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]]|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Spy Jail\">{{cite web|title=Falling in love with Pakistani spy cost Madhuri Gupta reputation, career & 3 years in jail|url=https://theprint.in/defence/falling-in-love-with-pakistani-spy-cost-madhuri-gupta-reputation-career-3-years-in-jail/60916/|publisher=The Print[|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> In 2012, media reports showed that a foreign service officer was fined US$1.5 million<ref name=\"IFS Fine Slavery\">{{cite web|title=US judge: Pay $1.5 m to maid of Indian diplomat for ill treatment|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/us-judge-pay-1-5-m-to-maid-of-indian-diplomat-for-ill-treatment/|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS torture\">{{cite web|title=US court asks Indian diplomat to pay $1.5m to 'tortured' maid|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/us-canada-news/US-court-asks-Indian-diplomat-to-pay-1-5m-to-tortured-maid/articleshow/12010886.cms|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> for engaging in slavery <ref name=\"IFS Fine Slavery\"/> by [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]]<ref name=\"IFS Fine Slavery\"/> and was also found denying visa on the basis of homosexuality.<ref name=\"IFS Visa denial 2012\">{{cite web|title=IFS officer denies visa to spouse of gay American diplomat, moved out|url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/ifs-officer-denies-visa-to-spouse-of-gay-diplomat-is-moved-out/1201023/|publisher=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Visa 2012\">{{cite web|title=IFS officer refuses visa to gay diplomat's spouse, transferred|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/ifs-officer-refuses-visa-to-gay-diplomats-spouse-transferred-1257167.html|publisher=[[Firstpost]]|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Shashi Tharoor]], currently the Chairman of the Parliamentary Standing Committee on External Affairs,<ref name=\"Lok Sabha\">{{cite web |url=http://164.100.47.192/Loksabha/Committee/Chairmen_Committees.aspx |title=Chairperson of Committees - Lok Sabha |work=[[Lok Sabha]] |accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rajya Sabha\">{{cite web |url=http://164.100.47.5/webcom/typewise.aspx?type=DRSCLS |title=Department Related Parliamentary Standing Committees (LS) |work=[[Rajya Sabha]] |accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> has presented 12th report<ref name=\"EA 12th Report IFS\">{{cite web |url=http://164.100.47.193/lsscommittee/External%20Affairs/16_External_Affairs_12.pdf |title=Twelfth Report, Standing Committee on External Affairs: IFS cadre|work=[[Lok Sabha]] |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> for expanding and building the numbers, quality and capacity of India's diplomats.<ref name=\"Shashi Tharoor Panel IFS\">{{cite web |url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/india-is-strapped-for-diplomats-but-if-shashi-tharoors-panel-has-its-way-you-could-become-one-2931362.html |title=If Shashi Tharoor's panel has its way, India's diplomatic corps could grow in quantity and quality |work=[[Firstpost]] |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Gap\">{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/fill-in-ifs-cadre-gap-parliament-committee-to-government/articleshow/53532710.cms |title=Fill in IFS cadre gap, Parliament committee to Government|work=[[The Economic Times]] |accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref> It has been reported that India's diplomatic corps is increasingly outclassed, outnumbered and out of date.<ref name=\"IFS MEA O\">{{cite web |url=https://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/ministry-eternal-affairs-0 |title=In the Ministry of Eternal Affairs|work=[[The Caravan]] |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> India has one of the most understaffed diplomatic force of any major country in the world.<ref name=\"IFS India US China\">{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/opinion/india-must-rethink-strategies-on-national-security-if-it-wants-to-join-ranks-with-us-china/270324/ |title=India must rethink strategies on national security if it wants to join ranks with US, China|work=The Print |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Foreign Influence\">{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/diplomacy/with-just-1400-diplomats-indias-foreign-influence-is-severely-limited/219288/ |title=With just 1,400 diplomats, India\u2019s foreign influence is severely limited|work=The Print |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Global\">{{cite web |url=https://theprint.in/india/governance/india-has-global-ambitions-but-not-enough-ifs-officers-to-fulfil-them/108990/ |title=India has global ambitions but not enough IFS officers to fulfil them|work=The Print |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS relevance\">{{cite web |url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/indian-foreign-service-in-desperate-need-of-reform-particularly-when-it-is-losing-relevance-2943924.html |title=Indian Foreign Service in desperate need of reform, particularly when it is losing relevance|work=[[Firstpost]] |accessdate=12 August 2019}}</ref> \n\n===Corruption and others===\nSeveral media reports have reported foreign service officers under investigation for corruption,<ref name=\"IFS Exchequer\">{{cite web|title=Milking the exchequer not foreign to IFS babus|url=https://timesofindia.com/india/Milking-the-exchequer-not-foreign-to-IFS-babus/articleshow/47873988.cms|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS CBI\">{{cite web|title=CBI to summon IFS officer Rakesh Kumar for questioning|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/cbi-to-summon-ifs-officer-rakesh-kumar-for-questioning/377172|publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS Scandal\">{{cite web|title=Scandal in Indian Foreign Service, 2 officers booked|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/mea-292292.html|publisher=[[CNN-News18]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"IFS UK\">{{cite web|title=Indian diplomats in UK face corruption allegations|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/20070430-corruption-allegations-to-uk-posted-indian-diplomats-748793-2007-04-30|publisher=[[India Today]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> sexual assault<ref name=\"IFS Sex Assault\">{{cite web|title=Woman Accuses IFS Officer of Sexual Assault|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newswire/story/woman-accuses-ifs-officer-of-sexual-assault/703628/?next|publisher=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)]]|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref> and financial irregularities for {{INRConvert|15|l|year=2020|lk=on}} per month.<ref name=\"IFS Financial\">{{cite web|title=Senior diplomat, who rented house for Rs 15 lakh a month, recalled for financial irregularities|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2019/dec/29/senior-diplomat-who-rented-house-for-rs-15-lakh-a-month-recalled-for-financial-irregularities-2082472.html|publisher=[[The New Indian Express]]|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign Service cadre discrimination===\nThere is in total a pool of 2,780 personnel holding diplomatic rank that serve in overseas missions and at headquarters. Of these only a minority of about 850 [https://www.mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm] are IFS officers, the senior cadre of Indian diplomacy, which is primarily drawn from recruitment through the Civil Services Examination. The breakdown of other cadres and personnel include 252 Grade-I officers of the IFS(B), 33 of the Interpreters Cadre, 24 of the Legal and Treaties Cadre, 635 Attaches, 540 diplomatic officers from the secretarial staff and 310 diplomatic officers from other Ministries.[https://www.scribd.com/document/320040429/External-Affairs#from_embed External Affairs | Test (Assessment) | Public Administration]\n\nIFS (B) is the subordinate cadre which ranks below the IFS (A) and has two sub-cadres, the IFS (B) General Cadre (recruited as Clerks and Assistants (now Assistant Section Officers)) and Stenographers Cadre (recruited as Stenographers and Personal Assistants) through separate entrance exams conducted by the Staff Selection Commission. The General Cadre, after promotion to Grade-I of the IFS (B), are absorbed into the IFS A service, while the Stenographers Cadre was denied this benefit vide a ruling in 2004 banning the lateral entry into IFS (A) upon promotion as Principal Private Secretaries (equivalent to Under Secretary in the IFS (B) General Cadre).<ref name=\"complaint\">{{cite news|last1=Mitra|first1=Devirupa|title=The class war in Foreign Service|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/The-class-war-in-Foreign-Service/2013/11/03/article1870174.ece1|publisher=New Indian Express|date=November 3, 2013}}</ref> The Stenographers Cadre provides secretarial support to the IFS Officers, while the IFS (B) General Cadre provides clerical support by manning the Sections and handling the files.<ref name=\"stenographer\">{{cite news|title=From steno to ambassador|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/thesundaystandard/article528329.ece?service=print|publisher=New Indian Express|date=May 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe relations between the cadres have been marked by territorial grievance and rivalry, becoming at times heated enough to spill into the public sphere.<ref name=\"complaint\"/> A common grievance among IFS (A) officers is the practice of antedating the appointment of IFS (B) officers 8 years before the date of their actual promotion.<ref name=\"complaint\"/> This puts the IFS (B) officers, who are seen as less prestigious, ahead for promotions of IFS (A) officers who directly entered the service before them.<ref name=\"complaint\"/> In 2013, 6 IFS (A) officers went as far as to lodge a complaint, against their foreign secretary as well as eight IFS (B) officers named as respondents, with the Central Administrative Tribunal (CAT) for clogging the promotion pipeline and leading to \"de-motivation and demoralisation among direct recruit officers\".<ref name=\"complaint\"/>\n\nIFS (B) officers have also complained of discrimination against them by IFS (A) officers. A Facebook group purportedly voicing the objections of IFS (B) officers sprung up in 2016 when IFS (B) officer Tajinder Singh, Second Secretary in the Indian embassy in [[Lisbon]] died of an apparent suicide.<ref name=\"unrest\">{{cite news|title=MEA facing unrest among junior IFS-B officers|url=http://www.indianmandarins.com/mea-facing-unrest-among-junior-ifs-b-officers/|publisher=Indian Mandarins|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref> The Facebook group alleged that Singh was treated unfairly because he was forced to yield his choice assignment in Washington DC after serving in a hardship posting in [[Damascus]].<ref name=\"unrest\"/> He was forced to give up his choice assignment for Lisbon because of alleged \"discrimination and professional challenges from IFS (A) officers in the ministry\".<ref name=\"unrest\"/>\n\nIFS (B) General Cadre have an acrimonious rivalry with the IFS (B) Stenographers Cadre, who are perceived to be lower in prestige than the IFS (B) officers but have a closer working relationship with IFS (A) officers, giving the stenographers at times promotion opportunities ahead of IFS (B) officers. This rivalry was brought to the fore when an officer of the stenographer cadre was appointed as Indian Ambassador to North Korea in 2012. Within a week of the appointment IFS (B) officers vociferously protested. Three different associations representing IFS (B) officers came together to write a single complaint to the Prime Minister\u2019s Office and the external affairs minister expressing their \u201cutter disappointment\u201d and requesting a review of the appointment. In this fight, the overall loss is for the Government of India since it fails to utilise services of the vast resource of experienced officers of the Stenographers Cadre, who by virtue of their attachments with senior officers, are better equipped of the soft policies of the Government in addition to the rules & regulations, compared to the General Cadre, who are mainly deployed in Sections and are limited to clerical work and maintaining files, till their promotion as Grade I. It has been a demand of the Stenographers Cadre that the Government should introduce merit-based scheme or a common exam for the subordinate cadres (Clerks as well as Stenographers) to select the best and the brightest officers for inclusion into the IFS (A) and filter out the incapable ones.<ref name=\"stenographer\"/>\n\n==Notable IFS Officers==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Vijayalakshmi Pandit]]\n*[[K.P.S. Menon]]\n*[[Maharaja Krishna Rasgotra]]\n*[[Shivshankar Menon]]\n*[[Nirupama Rao]]\n*[[Subimal Dutt]]\n*[[Kanwal Sibal]]\n*[[C. B. Muthamma]]\n*[[Shyam Saran]]\n*[[K. M. Panikkar]]\n*[[Triloki Nath Kaul]]\n*[[Brajesh Mishra]]\n*[[K. R. Narayanan]]\n*[[J N Dixit]]\n*[[Natwar Singh|K. Natwar Singh]]\n*[[Mani Shankar Aiyar]]\n*[[Mohammad Hamid Ansari]]\n*[[Hardeep Singh Puri]]\n*[[Sujatha Singh]]\n*[[S Jaishankar]]\n*[[Vijay Keshav Gokhale]]\n*[[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]]\n*[[Syed Akbaruddin]]\n*[[Vikas Swarup]]\n*[[Arundhati Ghose]]\n*[[Meira Kumar]]\n*[[Salman Haider]]\n*[[Shashank (diplomat) | Shashank]]\n{{div col end}}k\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website |1=http://mea.gov.in/indian-foreign-service.htm |name=Official website within the Ministry of External Affairs}}\n*[http://fsi.mea.gov.in/ Official website of Foreign Service Institute India]\n\n{{Public Services of India}}\n{{Civil service}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foreign Service}}\n[[Category:Central Civil Services (India)]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of India]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic services|Indian Foreign Service]]\n[[Category:Indian Foreign Service officers| ]]\n", "name_user": "Moharram586", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory:apply online passport part 2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Foreign_Service"}
{"title_page": "Joint Attack Helicopter Instrumented Evaluation", "text_new": "{{CSS image crop\n|Image = Bell AH-1 Cobra flying head on.jpg\n|bSize = 450\n|cWidth = 250\n|cHeight = 300\n|oTop = 100\n|oLeft = 85\n|Description=Masking their approach behind trees, TOW-firing Cobras proved to be devastatingly effective anti-tank weapons.\n}}\nThe '''Joint Attack Helicopter Instrumented Evaluation''' was a series of [[military exercise]]s that tested the use of [[attack helicopter]]s against simulated [[Warsaw Pact]] formations. They were carried out near [[Ansbach, Germany]] between March and May 1972, primarily by units of the US [[7th Army]] and the [[German Army]], with active participation from the [[Canadian Army]]. In historical works, they are often known as the '''Ansbach Tests'''.\n\nBlue Force was equipped primarily with [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW]]-firing [[Bell AH-1 Cobra|AH-1 Cobras]] supported by [[Bell OH-58 Kiowa|OH-58 Kiowa]] scout helicopters, while Red Force combined German [[Leopard 1|Leopard tank]]s and US [[M163 VADS|Vulcan air defense vehicles]] representing a typical [[Warsaw Pact]] (WTO) armored brigade. The outcome was overwhelmingly one-sided; Blue Force lost a total of 10 helicopters while destroying 167 tanks and 29 Vulcans.\n\nIn the 1950s, the [[NATO]] response to an attack by the WTO would be \"massive retaliation\" with [[tactical nuclear weapons]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.armscontrol.org/act/1999-07/features/natos-nuclear-weapons-rationale-first-use |title=NATO's Nuclear Weapons: The Rationale for 'No First Use' |first=Jack |last=Mendelsohn |websaite=Arms Control Today}}</ref> and conventional forces were seen as secondary. By the early 1970s this resulted in a huge disparity in tank numbers, with the WTO having about 14,000 tanks to NATOs 5,500.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=12}} The new [[Nixon Doctrine]]'s [[flexible response]] strategy required a non-nuclear answer to this disparity The Ansbach Tests suggested that this could be a force of a few hundred attack helicopters, which could be purchased and deployed for a fraction of the cost of an equivalent tank fleet.\n\nThis sparked off one of the most intense debates in the long history of tank-versus-antitank arguments. [[US Army]] doctrine to that point was that \"the best defense against a tank is another tank,\" but proponents of the helicopter claimed that \"the attack helicopter represents the final resolution of the tank-antitank debate\". In the years following the tests, the Army began converting their Cobras to the eight-TOW AH-1S model and changing their role to be primarily anti-tank vehicles.\n\n==Background==\nAnsbach was carried out as a result of several previous events and studies stretching out over a decade. Among them were the 1960 Rogers Board recommendations on Army aircraft development, which had comments about the development of the helicopter as a combat vehicle. In April 1962, [[Robert McNamara]] sent a directive to the Army to broaden its thinking about air operations and try to avoid inventing yet-another logistics vehicle.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=3}} These comments led to the formation of the [[Howze Board]], which enthusiastically supported the use of helicopters in combat. The increasing use and specialization of helicopters during the [[Vietnam War]] served to drive these concepts home, and in 1965 the Army began the Advanced Aerial Fire Support System (AAFSS) to develop its first dedicated [[attack helicopter]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Advanced Aerial Fire Support System |website=Global Security |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/aircraft/aafss.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, the [[British Army of the Rhine]] ran a series of tests known as [[Operation Hell Tank]] with the goal of testing the use of anti-tank missiles against simulated WTO forces. In one operation, Hell Tank IV, the helicopters ran up a 45-to-1 score over tanks that were executing a breakout. The tests also demonstrated that the helicopters were much less useful against tanks in defensive positions with their engines turned off, making them very difficult to spot from the air.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=The RUSI Journal |volume=121 |issue=2 |pages=53-62 |date=1976 |first=S. |last=Hickey |doi=10.1080/03071847609419264 |title=The British Army and the Battlefield Aerial Vehicle. The Way Ahead.}}</ref>\n\nWhile these events were occurring, in 1969 [[Richard Nixon]] formulated the [[Nixon Doctrine]], which called for the US to exit Vietnam and leave the combat to PAVN, a process later known as [[Vietnamization]]. It also re-focused the military on combat against Soviet-led forces in Europe.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=5}} Through this period the USSR had reached a level of parity in [[strategic nuclear weapons]], and US leaders concluded that employing nuclear weapons in any form might lead to mutual annihilation. As it stood, the WTO had an almost three-to-one superiority in tanks, which suggested NATO would lose a ground war with or without the use of [[tactical nuclear weapon]]s, and that only the \"macabre option\" of a strategic exchange might save it.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=12}} Given increasing fiscal restraint, the Army simply could not purchase enough tanks to offset this imbalance,{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=12}} and the attack helicopter appeared to be an alternative that was \"a relatively cheap, flexible and highly potent weapons system.\"{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=15}}\n\n==Trial by fire==\nThe AAFSS contents resulted in a complex design who's development dragged on for years before it was finally canceled. Looking for interim design to quickly deploy to Viet Nam, the [[AH-1 Cobra]] was introduced in combat in 1968.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Birth of the Cobra |first=Stephen |last=Joiner |magazine=Air and Space |date=August 2017 |url=https://www.airspacemag.com/military-aviation/13_aug2017-birth-of-the-cobra-180963930/}}</ref>\n\nBetween February and April 1971, the US and South Vietnamese [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam]] (ARVN) carried out [[Operation Lam Son 719]], the invasion of [[Laos]] in an effort to disrupt the [[Ho Chi Minh Trail]]. Over a period of time, the North's [[People's Army of Vietnam]] (PAVN) was able to amass a significant counter-invasion force, including extremely strong anti-aircraft forces and massed artillery. As these forces began to push ARVN out of Laos, Fire Base 31 was the subject of a classic armor attack by [[T-34]], [[T-55]] and [[PT-76]] tanks.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|pp=33-35}} This attack was met by rocket-firing Cobras. One post-action report noted that 47 tanks were attacked, and every one responded to the helicopter with its 12.7&nbsp;mm machine gun, but not one helicopter or crewman was lost. The helicopters outright destroyed six tanks, had nineteen \"mobility kills\" and a further eight damaged. Seeing this outcome, Army commanders noted that these helicopters had never been designed for anti-tank combat, and \"...had we entered Lamson 719 with a helicopter armed with an accurate, lethal, relatively long-range antitank weapon, we would have destroyed many more NVA tanks.\"{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\n[[File:Huey armed with TOW missiles in Vietnam.jpg|thumb|right|In 1972, two experimental TOW-firing UH-1's killed twenty-four tanks and dozens of other targets over a three week period without receiving a single hit.]]\n\nSuch a weapon arrived on 24 April 1972, when two experimental [[BGM-71 TOW]]-equipped [[Bell UH-1 Iroquois|UH-1B Huey]] were sent to [[Kon Tum]] during the [[Easter Offensive]]. After shakedown and crew training, they entered combat on 4 May and on their first mission killed four [[M41 Walker Bulldog]] tanks, a 2.5 ton truck, and a 105&nbsp;mm howitzer, all US-supplied equipment that had been captured from ARVN earlier in the campaign. Over the next weeks, the team killed dozens of targets of various sorts as PAVN prepared for an assault on Kon Tum.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\nThe battle opened in earnest on 25 May. The TOWs killed ten [[T-54]]s and added another two on the 27th, one of which the crew abandoned un-hit with the engine still running. In another case, a tank crew backed their tank into a house to avoid attack, only to be destroyed by a TOW fired in through a window.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Bright Shining Lie |first=Neil |last=Sheehan |date= 2009 |publisher=Doubleday |page=782 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=I_ECCk6SQQIC&pg=PA782}}</ref> By the time the battle ended on 12 June, they had accounted for 24 tanks, 2 [[armored personnel carriers|APCs]], 7 trucks, a twin 23&nbsp;mm anti-aircraft gun, a 122&nbsp;mm rocket launcher and many other targets.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\nThe two helicopters remained until 14 October, by which point they had fired 85 TOWs to produce 26 confirmed tank kills, 3 suspected tank kills, 15 wheeled vehicles destroyed, and 33 other point targets hit. During this entire time, neither helicopter received a single hit.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\n==Canadian interest==\nIn 1969, [[Pierre Trudeau]]'s [[Cabinet of Canada]] called into question the [[Canadian Army]]'s force structure in Europe, which was an expensive contingent to maintain given its low expected lifetime in combat. The existing tank support, based on the [[Centurion tank|Centurion]], was obsolete and needed replacement. Wishing to remove the nuclear strike mission as well, the Army was tasked with coming up with a new mission for the European force with a total contingent roughly half that of the existing force.{{sfn|Kasurak|2013|p=124}}\n\nConsidering the options, General [[Jean Victor Allard]] proposed a light force focused on anti-tank combat that could be rapidly deployed across Germany in order to stop WTO armored breakouts. The force was equipped mainly with [[M113]]s for mobility and armed with TOW and [[M47 Dragon]] missiles, as well as six Cobras and a number of to-be-determined Direct Fire Support Vehicles. A series of wargames in March 1970, \"Bronze Nimbus\", demonstrated the small force would inflict huge casualties on typical WTO formation, but invariably the sheer number of WTO tanks ate up their ammunition and overwhelmed them.{{sfn|Maas|2017|p=57}}\n\nThis led the Army to consider becoming a completely airmobile force, adding more attack helicopters to the mix, and using the hunter/killer structure developed in Vietnam.{{sfn|Kasurak|2013|p=126}} While data from Vietnam was useful, it was not clear how this force would fair in Europe given the WTO's much stronger organic air defenses. Basing the entire future of the Canadian Army's European presence would demand better data and testing if it were to go forward.{{sfn|Kasurak|2013|p=136}}{{sfn|Maas|2017|p=58}}\n\n==Tests==\n[[File:Cobra and Kiowa DF-ST-86-10445.JPEG|thumb|right|Ansbach demonstrated the value of the \"hunter/killer\" teams combining the Cobra gunship and Kiowa scout.]]\n[[File:ZSU-23-4-Camp-Pendleton.jpg|thumb|right|Ansbach suggested the ''Shilka'' was easy prey for helicopters using pop-up attacks.]]\n\nAll of these changes resulted in intense interest in helicopter combat in the US, Canada and, increasingly, the German [[Bundeswehr]]. The [[United States Army Europe]] began forming plans for extensive tests of helicopter combat for early 1972, with German and Canadian participation. The WTO forces would be made up from Bundeswehr [[Leopard tank]]s and US [[M163 VADS]] playing the part of the [[ZSU-23-4 Shilka]], which had no direct counterpart in NATO.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=26}} [[Laser]]s were used by all vehicles to simulate weapons fire, and laser receivers firing [[smoke grenade]]s registered hits.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=25}}{{sfn|Bell|Cocke|1974|p=41}}\n\nTwo types of combat scenarios were considered. In one, a single AH-1G Cobra attack helicopter simulating a TOW-equipped AH-1Q was paired with two OH-58 helicopters providing forward observation. This sort of \"hunter/killer\" team had been used to great effect in Vietnam. It was not clear this was suitable in an armor-heavy battle expected in Europe, so the same setups were repeated with two Cobras and no Kiohas. Groups of three Leopards with one Vulcan attempted to move forward against this opposition.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=26}} Three separate scenarios were trialed. In the first, the helicopters were working in concert with in-place defensive forces, acting as additional anti-tank weapons. In the second, the goal was to delay an attacking force to give time for other forces to get into position to defend against them. In the third, the helicopters were being sent against a successful armored breakthrough with the goal being to kill as many vehicles as possible.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}} A total of 60 trial runs were conducted.{{sfn|Bell|Cocke|1974|p=41}}\n\nAs might be expected, in the breakout scenario the helicopters benefited from a lack of information on the part of the attackers, which were repeatedly engaged at long range and often had no idea there was a helicopter nearby.{{sfn|McGowen|2005|p=158}} The value of the hunter/killer teams, in this case, was clear in the results; when acting alone in this scenario, the helicopters often blundered into the tanks and this resulted in the highest losses, six attack helicopters. However, this scenario also resulted in the highest total losses to the attacking force, with 73 vehicles killed, for an exchange ratio of 12 to 1. Over the entire series of runs, the hunter/killer teams killed 167 vehicles for the loss of 6 helicopters for an exchange of 11 to 1, and the all-attack teams killed 127 vehicles for six losses, a ratio of almost 15 to 1.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}\n\nThe takeaway results of the tests were twofold:\n\n{{quote|The inclusion of scout helicopters in the antiarmor team is essential and noticeably enhances the survivability of the missile firing aircraft.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}}}\n\nand:\n\n{{quote|Pilots effectively employed nap-of-the-earth flight techniques to conceal their presence and, when they were acquired, usually presented fleeting targets.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}}}\n\nSerious questions about the reality of these simulations were raised. Most obvious was the lack of air missions on the Red Force side, which it was suggested would at least restrict the mobility of the helicopters. Additionally, the strong artillery backing normally present could be an effective anti-helicopter weapon, or at least drive them away from good ambush spots. Finally, no reconnaissance forces were present on the Red Force side, which might spot the helicopters before the vehicles approached. Another concern was that the Cobra was only equipped for daytime attacks in good weather, and concerns were raised that European weather would not allow them to operate at the required level.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=28}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe most immediate effect of the Ansbach tests was the reopening of the debate about the obsolescence of the tank on the modern battlefield. That the tank was the primary weapon of the anti-tank defense had risen to the point of being official doctrine; FM 17-1 stated that \"The tank is the primary armor-defeating weapon of armored formations.\" Ansbach caused those in support of the helicopter to claim the era of the tank was over, or as one observer put it:\n\n{{quote|For the advocates of airmobility, the attack helicopter represents the final resolution of the tank-antitank debate. For the protagonists, the attack helicopter represents a pipedream that will be quickly and devastatingly shattered by the reality of combat.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}}}\n\nThe tests had been carried out just as the new [[M1 Abrams|XM-1]] tank began its design cycle and was spearheading a renewed interest in tanks. This was bolstered by the events in the [[Yom Kippur War]] of 1973, where the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) \"utterly defeated combined armies equal in strength to NATO Europe\" and suggested that it was \"obvious that armor is battlefield-decisive so long as it is used wisely.\"{{sfn|Brower|1974|p=15}}\n\n==THES==\nLooking to gain further clarity as the debate about the Ansbach results, the Army commissioned BDM International, now part of [[Vinnell]], to prepare a follow-up theoretical study. The Tactical Helicopter Employment Study, or THES, was largely a literature search, an attempt to find and collect all useful information on the topic of attack helicopters to date.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=31}} Published in November 1973, THES made three broad conclusions:{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=32}}\n\n# previous experiments and operations generally supported each other's results\n# doctrines developed during these events appeared to be correct and well accepted\n# the attack helicopter could be used as a primary anti-armor weapon\n\nTHES also considered the issue of weather, and using data collected from sixteen sites over a ten-year span, they concluded that the Cobra could fly 91% of the time, even during the worst weather in November and December.<ref>{{cite techreport |url=https://archive.org/stream/DTIC_ADA147750/DTIC_ADA147750_djvu.txt |title=Determining the Optimum Aviation Organization for the Operational Level of War |first=Carlton |last=Hood |date=May 1984 |publisher=United States Army}}</ref>\n\n==Outcomes==\nIn 1976, as a direct result of the tests and the THEL results, the Army began updating all AH-1G, -1Q and -1R to the modernized AH-1S. The -1S retained the Cobra's direct-fire capabilities with rockets and guns, but shifted its primary mission to anti-tank, carrying eight TOW missiles. In March 1978, a further 100 new-build AH-1S's were ordered.{{sfn|McGowen|2005|p=158}}\n\nIn Canada, the tests were used to bolster arguments for the new mobile force structure. However, when the cost of the helicopters was considered, it appeared there was only enough money to equip one formation with the required number of aircraft. This would leave the forces in Canada both under-equipped and lacking training.{{sfn|Maas|2017|p=59}} Having repeatedly suggested a ''status quo'' approach, updating the Centurions in both Europe and Canada, a wait and see approach developed. An additional factor in the Canadian decision was the advocacy of Major Norman Shackleton, who wrote a series of influential and widely quoted pro-tank articles throughout this period. Among these was a 1967 article that concluded: \"... the foremost antitank weapon is probably another tank sited in the defense.\"<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Military Review |volume=47 |date=July 1967 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=qGU3r9LVwbsC&pg=PA58 |title=The Case for the Defense |first=Norman |last=Shackleton}}</ref> By the early 1980s, the helicopter contingent had not been purchased, while a new tank contingent of Leopards was purchased from Germany in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |website=The Drive |title=Canada Has Given Up Trying To Find A Good Home For Its Retired Leopard Tanks |date=9 July 2018 |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/22044/canada-has-given-up-trying-to-find-a-good-home-for-its-retired-leopard-tanks}}</ref>\n\nOther NATO forces also began the process of integrating attack helicopters into their forces, initially with ''ad hoc'' conversions of existing utility designs like the [[Westland Scout]]<ref>{{cite magazine | last=Ferguson | first= James | title =Commando aviation |magazine= Flight International | date =6 February 1982 | url = http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1982/1982%20-%200314.html | accessdate =16 November 2014 |ref=harv}}</ref> and [[MBB Bo 105]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eads.com/1024/en/eads/history/airhist/1970_today/bo105_1971.html |title=B\u00f6lkow Bo 105 - History of EADS |publisher=EADS |accessdate=2007-03-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929110626/http://www.eads.com/1024/en/eads/history/airhist/1970_today/bo105_1971.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Exercise Hell Tank]], a similar [[British Army]] test in 1966 that was even more in favor of helicopters\n* [[J-CATCH]], testing attack helicopters against [[fighter aircraft]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite techreport\n |first=Curtis |last=Ebitz\n |title= The Tank-Attack Helicopter In The European Mid-Intensity Conflict Environment\n |url=https://apps.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/b006705.pdf\n |date=6 June 1975\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=EklRAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PA4\n |title=Armor in the October War\n |date=May-June 1974\n |journal=Armor\n |volume=83\n |first=Kenneth |last=Brower\n |pages=10-15\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=A National Force: The Evolution of Canada's Army, 1950-2000\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=VTIAAQAAQBAJ\n |first=Peter |last=Kasurak\n |publisher=UBC Press\n |date=2013\n |isbn=9780774826419\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=The Price of Alliance\n |first=Frank |last=Maas\n |date=2017\n |publisher=UBC Press\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=qLo4DwAAQBAJ\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=Department of the Army Historical Summary, Fiscal Year 1973\n |first1=Willian |last1= Bell\n |first2=Karl |last2=Cocke\n |url=https://history.army.mil/books/DAHSUM/1973/chIII.htm\n |date=1974\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |first=Stanley |last=McGowen\n |title=Helicopters: An Illustrated History of Their Impact\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xLis8p7uLaUC&pg=PA158\n |publisher=ABC-CLIO\n |date=2005\n |ref=harv\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{cite journal\n |first=Norman |last=Shackleton\n |title=Will the Tank Go the Way of the Horse?\n |date=September-October 1968\n |pages=4-8\n |journal=Armor\n |volume=77 |number=5\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=eIJNAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PA4\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |first=John |last=Burns\n |title= XM-26 TOW: Birth of the Helicopter as a Tank Buster\n |publisher=United States Army\n |date=1994\n |url=http://www.angelfire.com/ga2/vnhistory/2RAC.html\n}}\n\n[[Category:Military exercises involving the United States]]\n[[Category:Military exercises and wargames]]\n[[Category:Canadian military exercises\u200e]]\n[[Category:Military aviation exercises]]\n", "text_old": "{{CSS image crop\n|Image = Bell AH-1 Cobra flying head on.jpg\n|bSize = 450\n|cWidth = 250\n|cHeight = 300\n|oTop = 100\n|oLeft = 85\n|Description=Masking their approach behind trees, TOW-firing Cobras proved to be devastatingly effective anti-tank weapons.\n}}\nThe '''Joint Attack Helicopter Instrumented Evaluation''' was a series of [[military exercise]]s that tested the use of [[attack helicopter]]s against simulated [[Warsaw Pact]] formations. They were carried out near [[Ansbach, Germany]] between March and May 1972, primarily by units of the US [[7th Army]] and the [[German Army]], with active participation from the [[Canadian Army]]. In historical works, they are often known as the '''Ansbach Tests'''.\n\nBlue Force was equipped primarily with [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW]]-firing [[Bell AH-1 Cobra|AH-1 Cobras]] supported by [[Bell OH-58 Kiowa|OH-58 Kiowa]] scout helicopters, while Red Force combined German [[Leopard 1|Leopard tank]]s and US [[M163 VADS|Vulcan air defense vehicles]] representing a typical [[Warsaw Pact]] (WTO) armored brigade. The outcome was overwhelmingly one-sided; Blue Force lost a total of 10 helicopters while destroying 167 tanks and 29 Vulcans.\n\nIn the 1950s, the [[NATO]] response to an attack by the WTO would be \"massive retaliation\" with [[tactical nuclear weapons]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.armscontrol.org/act/1999-07/features/natos-nuclear-weapons-rationale-first-use |title=NATO's Nuclear Weapons: The Rationale for 'No First Use' |first=Jack |last=Mendelsohn |websaite=Arms Control Today}}</ref> and conventional forces were seen as secondary. By the early 1970s this resulted in a huge disparity in tank numbers, with the WTO having about 14,000 tanks to NATOs 5,500.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=12}} Under the new [[Nixon Doctrine]]'s [[flexible response]] strategy, a non-nuclear answer to this disparity was needed. The Ansbach Tests suggested that this could be a force of a few hundred attack helicopters, which could be purchased and deployed for a fraction of the cost of an equivalent tank fleet.\n\nThis sparked off one of the most intense debates in the long history of tank-versus-antitank arguments. [[US Army]] doctrine to that point was that \"the best defense against a tank is another tank,\" but proponents of the helicopter claimed that \"the attack helicopter represents the final resolution of the tank-antitank debate\". In the years following the tests, the Army began converting their Cobras to the eight-TOW AH-1S model and changing their role to be primarily anti-tank vehicles.\n\n==Background==\nAnsbach was carried out as a result of several previous events and studies stretching out over a decade. Among them were the 1960 Rogers Board recommendations on Army aircraft development, which had comments about the development of the helicopter as a combat vehicle. In April 1962, [[Robert McNamara]] sent a directive to the Army to broaden its thinking about air operations and try to avoid inventing yet-another logistics vehicle.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=3}} These comments led to the formation of the [[Howze Board]], which enthusiastically supported the use of helicopters in combat. The increasing use and specialization of helicopters during the [[Vietnam War]] served to drive these concepts home, and in 1965 the Army began the Advanced Aerial Fire Support System (AAFSS) to develop its first dedicated [[attack helicopter]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Advanced Aerial Fire Support System |website=Global Security |url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/aircraft/aafss.htm}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, the [[British Army of the Rhine]] ran a series of tests known as [[Operation Hell Tank]] with the goal of testing the use of anti-tank missiles against simulated WTO forces. In one operation, Hell Tank IV, the helicopters ran up a 45-to-1 score over tanks that were executing a breakout. The tests also demonstrated that the helicopters were much less useful against tanks in defensive positions with their engines turned off, making them very difficult to spot from the air.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=The RUSI Journal |volume=121 |issue=2 |pages=53-62 |date=1976 |first=S. |last=Hickey |doi=10.1080/03071847609419264 |title=The British Army and the Battlefield Aerial Vehicle. The Way Ahead.}}</ref>\n\nWhile these events were occurring, in 1969 [[Richard Nixon]] formulated the [[Nixon Doctrine]], which called for the US to exit Vietnam and leave the combat to PAVN, a process later known as [[Vietnamization]]. It also re-focused the military on combat against Soviet-led forces in Europe.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=5}} Through this period the USSR had reached a level of parity in [[strategic nuclear weapons]], and US leaders concluded that employing nuclear weapons in any form might lead to mutual annihilation. As it stood, the WTO had an almost three-to-one superiority in tanks, which suggested NATO would lose a ground war with or without the use of [[tactical nuclear weapon]]s, and that only the \"macabre option\" of a strategic exchange might save it.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=12}} Given increasing fiscal restraint, the Army simply could not purchase enough tanks to offset this imbalance,{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=12}} and the attack helicopter appeared to be an alternative that was \"a relatively cheap, flexible and highly potent weapons system.\"{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=15}}\n\n==Trial by fire==\nThe AAFSS contents resulted in a complex design who's development dragged on for years before it was finally canceled. Looking for interim design to quickly deploy to Viet Nam, the [[AH-1 Cobra]] was introduced in combat in 1968.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Birth of the Cobra |first=Stephen |last=Joiner |magazine=Air and Space |date=August 2017 |url=https://www.airspacemag.com/military-aviation/13_aug2017-birth-of-the-cobra-180963930/}}</ref>\n\nBetween February and April 1971, the US and South Vietnamese [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam]] (ARVN) carried out [[Operation Lam Son 719]], the invasion of [[Laos]] in an effort to disrupt the [[Ho Chi Minh Trail]]. Over a period of time, the North's [[People's Army of Vietnam]] (PAVN) was able to amass a significant counter-invasion force, including extremely strong anti-aircraft forces and massed artillery. As these forces began to push ARVN out of Laos, Fire Base 31 was the subject of a classic armor attack by [[T-34]], [[T-55]] and [[PT-76]] tanks.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|pp=33-35}} This attack was met by rocket-firing Cobras. One post-action report noted that 47 tanks were attacked, and every one responded to the helicopter with its 12.7&nbsp;mm machine gun, but not one helicopter or crewman was lost. The helicopters outright destroyed six tanks, had nineteen \"mobility kills\" and a further eight damaged. Seeing this outcome, Army commanders noted that these helicopters had never been designed for anti-tank combat, and \"...had we entered Lamson 719 with a helicopter armed with an accurate, lethal, relatively long-range antitank weapon, we would have destroyed many more NVA tanks.\"{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\n[[File:Huey armed with TOW missiles in Vietnam.jpg|thumb|right|In 1972, two experimental TOW-firing UH-1's killed twenty-four tanks and dozens of other targets over a three week period without receiving a single hit.]]\n\nSuch a weapon arrived on 24 April 1972, when two experimental [[BGM-71 TOW]]-equipped [[Bell UH-1 Iroquois|UH-1B Huey]] were sent to [[Kon Tum]] during the [[Easter Offensive]]. After shakedown and crew training, they entered combat on 4 May and on their first mission killed four [[M41 Walker Bulldog]] tanks, a 2.5 ton truck, and a 105&nbsp;mm howitzer, all US-supplied equipment that had been captured from ARVN earlier in the campaign. Over the next weeks, the team killed dozens of targets of various sorts as PAVN prepared for an assault on Kon Tum.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\nThe battle opened in earnest on 25 May. The TOWs killed ten [[T-54]]s and added another two on the 27th, one of which the crew abandoned un-hit with the engine still running. In another case, a tank crew backed their tank into a house to avoid attack, only to be destroyed by a TOW fired in through a window.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Bright Shining Lie |first=Neil |last=Sheehan |date= 2009 |publisher=Doubleday |page=782 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=I_ECCk6SQQIC&pg=PA782}}</ref> By the time the battle ended on 12 June, they had accounted for 24 tanks, 2 [[armored personnel carriers|APCs]], 7 trucks, a twin 23&nbsp;mm anti-aircraft gun, a 122&nbsp;mm rocket launcher and many other targets.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\nThe two helicopters remained until 14 October, by which point they had fired 85 TOWs to produce 26 confirmed tank kills, 3 suspected tank kills, 15 wheeled vehicles destroyed, and 33 other point targets hit. During this entire time, neither helicopter received a single hit.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=35}}\n\n==Canadian interest==\nIn 1969, [[Pierre Trudeau]]'s [[Cabinet of Canada]] called into question the [[Canadian Army]]'s force structure in Europe, which was an expensive contingent to maintain given its low expected lifetime in combat. The existing tank support, based on the [[Centurion tank|Centurion]], was obsolete and needed replacement. Wishing to remove the nuclear strike mission as well, the Army was tasked with coming up with a new mission for the European force with a total contingent roughly half that of the existing force.{{sfn|Kasurak|2013|p=124}}\n\nConsidering the options, General [[Jean Victor Allard]] proposed a light force focused on anti-tank combat that could be rapidly deployed across Germany in order to stop WTO armored breakouts. The force was equipped mainly with [[M113]]s for mobility and armed with TOW and [[M47 Dragon]] missiles, as well as six Cobras and a number of to-be-determined Direct Fire Support Vehicles. A series of wargames in March 1970, \"Bronze Nimbus\", demonstrated the small force would inflict huge casualties on typical WTO formation, but invariably the sheer number of WTO tanks ate up their ammunition and overwhelmed them.{{sfn|Maas|2017|p=57}}\n\nThis led the Army to consider becoming a completely airmobile force, adding more attack helicopters to the mix, and using the hunter/killer structure developed in Vietnam.{{sfn|Kasurak|2013|p=126}} While data from Vietnam was useful, it was not clear how this force would fair in Europe given the WTO's much stronger organic air defenses. Basing the entire future of the Canadian Army's European presence would demand better data and testing if it were to go forward.{{sfn|Kasurak|2013|p=136}}{{sfn|Maas|2017|p=58}}\n\n==Tests==\n[[File:Cobra and Kiowa DF-ST-86-10445.JPEG|thumb|right|Ansbach demonstrated the value of the \"hunter/killer\" teams combining the Cobra gunship and Kiowa scout.]]\n[[File:ZSU-23-4-Camp-Pendleton.jpg|thumb|right|Ansbach suggested the ''Shilka'' was easy prey for helicopters using pop-up attacks.]]\n\nAll of these changes resulted in intense interest in helicopter combat in the US, Canada and, increasingly, the German [[Bundeswehr]]. The [[United States Army Europe]] began forming plans for extensive tests of helicopter combat for early 1972, with German and Canadian participation. The WTO forces would be made up from Bundeswehr [[Leopard tank]]s and US [[M163 VADS]] playing the part of the [[ZSU-23-4 Shilka]], which had no direct counterpart in NATO.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=26}} [[Laser]]s were used by all vehicles to simulate weapons fire, and laser receivers firing [[smoke grenade]]s registered hits.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=25}}{{sfn|Bell|Cocke|1974|p=41}}\n\nTwo types of combat scenarios were considered. In one, a single AH-1G Cobra attack helicopter simulating a TOW-equipped AH-1Q was paired with two OH-58 helicopters providing forward observation. This sort of \"hunter/killer\" team had been used to great effect in Vietnam. It was not clear this was suitable in an armor-heavy battle expected in Europe, so the same setups were repeated with two Cobras and no Kiohas. Groups of three Leopards with one Vulcan attempted to move forward against this opposition.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=26}} Three separate scenarios were trialed. In the first, the helicopters were working in concert with in-place defensive forces, acting as additional anti-tank weapons. In the second, the goal was to delay an attacking force to give time for other forces to get into position to defend against them. In the third, the helicopters were being sent against a successful armored breakthrough with the goal being to kill as many vehicles as possible.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}} A total of 60 trial runs were conducted.{{sfn|Bell|Cocke|1974|p=41}}\n\nAs might be expected, in the breakout scenario the helicopters benefited from a lack of information on the part of the attackers, which were repeatedly engaged at long range and often had no idea there was a helicopter nearby.{{sfn|McGowen|2005|p=158}} The value of the hunter/killer teams, in this case, was clear in the results; when acting alone in this scenario, the helicopters often blundered into the tanks and this resulted in the highest losses, six attack helicopters. However, this scenario also resulted in the highest total losses to the attacking force, with 73 vehicles killed, for an exchange ratio of 12 to 1. Over the entire series of runs, the hunter/killer teams killed 167 vehicles for the loss of 6 helicopters for an exchange of 11 to 1, and the all-attack teams killed 127 vehicles for six losses, a ratio of almost 15 to 1.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}\n\nThe takeaway results of the tests were twofold:\n\n{{quote|The inclusion of scout helicopters in the antiarmor team is essential and noticeably enhances the survivability of the missile firing aircraft.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}}}\n\nand:\n\n{{quote|Pilots effectively employed nap-of-the-earth flight techniques to conceal their presence and, when they were acquired, usually presented fleeting targets.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}}}\n\nSerious questions about the reality of these simulations were raised. Most obvious was the lack of air missions on the Red Force side, which it was suggested would at least restrict the mobility of the helicopters. Additionally, the strong artillery backing normally present could be an effective anti-helicopter weapon, or at least drive them away from good ambush spots. Finally, no reconnaissance forces were present on the Red Force side, which might spot the helicopters before the vehicles approached. Another concern was that the Cobra was only equipped for daytime attacks in good weather, and concerns were raised that European weather would not allow them to operate at the required level.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=28}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe most immediate effect of the Ansbach tests was the reopening of the debate about the obsolescence of the tank on the modern battlefield. That the tank was the primary weapon of the anti-tank defense had risen to the point of being official doctrine; FM 17-1 stated that \"The tank is the primary armor-defeating weapon of armored formations.\" Ansbach caused those in support of the helicopter to claim the era of the tank was over, or as one observer put it:\n\n{{quote|For the advocates of airmobility, the attack helicopter represents the final resolution of the tank-antitank debate. For the protagonists, the attack helicopter represents a pipedream that will be quickly and devastatingly shattered by the reality of combat.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=27}}}}\n\nThe tests had been carried out just as the new [[M1 Abrams|XM-1]] tank began its design cycle and was spearheading a renewed interest in tanks. This was bolstered by the events in the [[Yom Kippur War]] of 1973, where the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) \"utterly defeated combined armies equal in strength to NATO Europe\" and suggested that it was \"obvious that armor is battlefield-decisive so long as it is used wisely.\"{{sfn|Brower|1974|p=15}}\n\n==THES==\nLooking to gain further clarity as the debate about the Ansbach results, the Army commissioned BDM International, now part of [[Vinnell]], to prepare a follow-up theoretical study. The Tactical Helicopter Employment Study, or THES, was largely a literature search, an attempt to find and collect all useful information on the topic of attack helicopters to date.{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=31}} Published in November 1973, THES made three broad conclusions:{{sfn|Ebitz|1975|p=32}}\n\n# previous experiments and operations generally supported each other's results\n# doctrines developed during these events appeared to be correct and well accepted\n# the attack helicopter could be used as a primary anti-armor weapon\n\nTHES also considered the issue of weather, and using data collected from sixteen sites over a ten-year span, they concluded that the Cobra could fly 91% of the time, even during the worst weather in November and December.<ref>{{cite techreport |url=https://archive.org/stream/DTIC_ADA147750/DTIC_ADA147750_djvu.txt |title=Determining the Optimum Aviation Organization for the Operational Level of War |first=Carlton |last=Hood |date=May 1984 |publisher=United States Army}}</ref>\n\n==Outcomes==\nIn 1976, as a direct result of the tests and the THEL results, the Army began updating all AH-1G, -1Q and -1R to the modernized AH-1S. The -1S retained the Cobra's direct-fire capabilities with rockets and guns, but shifted its primary mission to anti-tank, carrying eight TOW missiles. In March 1978, a further 100 new-build AH-1S's were ordered.{{sfn|McGowen|2005|p=158}}\n\nIn Canada, the tests were used to bolster arguments for the new mobile force structure. However, when the cost of the helicopters was considered, it appeared there was only enough money to equip one formation with the required number of aircraft. This would leave the forces in Canada both under-equipped and lacking training.{{sfn|Maas|2017|p=59}} Having repeatedly suggested a ''status quo'' approach, updating the Centurions in both Europe and Canada, a wait and see approach developed. An additional factor in the Canadian decision was the advocacy of Major Norman Shackleton, who wrote a series of influential and widely quoted pro-tank articles throughout this period. Among these was a 1967 article that concluded: \"... the foremost antitank weapon is probably another tank sited in the defense.\"<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Military Review |volume=47 |date=July 1967 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=qGU3r9LVwbsC&pg=PA58 |title=The Case for the Defense |first=Norman |last=Shackleton}}</ref> By the early 1980s, the helicopter contingent had not been purchased, while a new tank contingent of Leopards was purchased from Germany in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |website=The Drive |title=Canada Has Given Up Trying To Find A Good Home For Its Retired Leopard Tanks |date=9 July 2018 |url=https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/22044/canada-has-given-up-trying-to-find-a-good-home-for-its-retired-leopard-tanks}}</ref>\n\nOther NATO forces also began the process of integrating attack helicopters into their forces, initially with ''ad hoc'' conversions of existing utility designs like the [[Westland Scout]]<ref>{{cite magazine | last=Ferguson | first= James | title =Commando aviation |magazine= Flight International | date =6 February 1982 | url = http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1982/1982%20-%200314.html | accessdate =16 November 2014 |ref=harv}}</ref> and [[MBB Bo 105]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eads.com/1024/en/eads/history/airhist/1970_today/bo105_1971.html |title=B\u00f6lkow Bo 105 - History of EADS |publisher=EADS |accessdate=2007-03-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929110626/http://www.eads.com/1024/en/eads/history/airhist/1970_today/bo105_1971.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Exercise Hell Tank]], a similar [[British Army]] test in 1966 that was even more in favor of helicopters\n* [[J-CATCH]], testing attack helicopters against [[fighter aircraft]]\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite techreport\n |first=Curtis |last=Ebitz\n |title= The Tank-Attack Helicopter In The European Mid-Intensity Conflict Environment\n |url=https://apps.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/b006705.pdf\n |date=6 June 1975\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=EklRAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PA4\n |title=Armor in the October War\n |date=May-June 1974\n |journal=Armor\n |volume=83\n |first=Kenneth |last=Brower\n |pages=10-15\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=A National Force: The Evolution of Canada's Army, 1950-2000\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=VTIAAQAAQBAJ\n |first=Peter |last=Kasurak\n |publisher=UBC Press\n |date=2013\n |isbn=9780774826419\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=The Price of Alliance\n |first=Frank |last=Maas\n |date=2017\n |publisher=UBC Press\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=qLo4DwAAQBAJ\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title=Department of the Army Historical Summary, Fiscal Year 1973\n |first1=Willian |last1= Bell\n |first2=Karl |last2=Cocke\n |url=https://history.army.mil/books/DAHSUM/1973/chIII.htm\n |date=1974\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |first=Stanley |last=McGowen\n |title=Helicopters: An Illustrated History of Their Impact\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xLis8p7uLaUC&pg=PA158\n |publisher=ABC-CLIO\n |date=2005\n |ref=harv\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{cite journal\n |first=Norman |last=Shackleton\n |title=Will the Tank Go the Way of the Horse?\n |date=September-October 1968\n |pages=4-8\n |journal=Armor\n |volume=77 |number=5\n |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=eIJNAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PA4\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |first=John |last=Burns\n |title= XM-26 TOW: Birth of the Helicopter as a Tank Buster\n |publisher=United States Army\n |date=1994\n |url=http://www.angelfire.com/ga2/vnhistory/2RAC.html\n}}